| style=&quot;background: #f7f6f6;&quot;|Medo-Persia   
| style=&quot;background: #ffee7a;&quot;|Macedonia   
| style=&quot;background: #e2e2e0;&quot;|Ptolemys and Seleucids   
| style=&quot;background:tan;&quot;|Romans   
| style=&quot;background: #cdfcfd;&quot;|Future antichristian empire   
|}

* Other scholars argue that there was a split between the [[Medes]] and [[Persian empire|Persians]].&lt;ref&gt;A short introduction to the Hebrew Bible, John J. Collins, p. 282&lt;/ref&gt;

Separate issues:

''The following statements are archetypical, and do not represent every variant of this mode of interpreting Daniel's kingdoms:''

* [[Jewish eschatology|Jewish]] and Christian [[Historicism (Christianity)|Historicists]] (as generally taught in the Catholic, Orthodox, and Protestant Churches [see [[Historicism (Christianity)]]]) believe that the fulfillment of the prophecies of Daniel continue in a straight line through to the End of the Age.

* [[Jewish eschatology|Jewish]] and Christian [[Futurism (Christian eschatology)|Futurists]], [[Dispensationalism|Dispensationalists]], and, to some degree, [[Partial preterism|Partial Preterists]] believe that the prophecies of Daniel stopped with the destruction of the Second Temple of Jerusalem and will resume at some point in the future after a gap in prophecy that accounts for the Church Age.

* [[Reconstructionist Judaism|Jewish Reconstructionists]] and [[Preterism|Full Preterists]] believe that Daniel is completely fulfilled, and that the believers are now working to establish the Kingdom of God on earth.

====Other views====

Others like Walton have advocated a combination of both schemes, but in different parts of Daniel.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.biblicalstudies.org.uk/article_daniel_walton.html &quot;The Four Kingdoms Of Daniel&quot;] by John H. Walton, ''Journal of the Evangelical Theological Society'' 29.1 (1986): 25-36.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Language===
Scholars have speculated about the bilingual literary structure of Daniel - Chapters 2 through 7 in Aramaic, the rest in Hebrew.  One of the most frequent speculations is that the entire book (excepting 9:4-20) was originally written in Aramaic, with portions translated into Hebrew, possibly to increase acceptance&lt;ref&gt;Hartman and Di Lella, (1990), 408.&lt;/ref&gt; - many Aramaisms in the Hebrew text find proposed explanation by the hypothesis of an inexact initial translation into Hebrew.

According to John Collins in his 1993 commentary, ''Daniel, Hermeneia Commentary'', the Aramaic in Daniel is of a later form than that used in the Samaria correspondence, but slightly earlier than the form used in the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]], meaning that the Aramaic chapters 2-6 may have been written earlier in the Hellenistic period than the rest of the book, with the vision in chapter 7 being the only Aramaic portion dating to the time of Antiochus.  The Hebrew portion is, for all intents and purposes, identical to that found in the Dead Sea Scrolls, meaning chapters 1 and 8-12 were in existence before the late 2nd century BC.&lt;ref&gt;Daniel, Hermeneia Commentary&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web
  | title = The Skeptical Review Online
  | url = http://www.infidels.org/library/magazines/tsr/2001/3/013mail.html 2
  | accessdate = }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Contrary to the above, the ''Expositor's Bible Commentary'' (Zondervan, 1990) claims that the language of Daniel, in comparison with the Hebrew and Aramaic texts of the Hellenistic period, &quot;prove quite conclusively to any scholar that the second-century date and Palestinian provenance of the Book of Daniel cannot be upheld any longer without violence being done to the science of linguistics.&quot; It adds that the serious mistakes of the Septuagint to render many Persian and Accadian terms, as the offices mentioned in Dan. 3:3, proves ignorance of words of the old past, already forgotten in the Hellenistic period, indicating that the Book of Daniel was written in the late 6th century BC.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;There is no possibility that the text of Daniel could have been composed as late as the Maccabean uprising, and that there is every likelihood that the Aramaic comes from the same period, if not a century earlier, than the Aramaic of the [[Elephantine Papyri]] and of Ezra, which are admittedly fifth-century productions. It goes without saying that if the predictions concerning the period of Antiochus III and Antiochus IV (222-164 BC) are composed in language antedating the second-century and third-century B.C., then the whole effort to explain Daniel as a vaticinium ex eventu must be abandoned.&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

E.C. Lucas is more cautious in his assessment of linguistic arguments as well. Evaluating Collins' approach, he considers &quot;the wide geographical spread from which the material comes and the implicit assumption that linguistic developments would have occurred uniformly throughout this area&quot; a weakness and concludes, &quot;The character of the Hebrew and Aramaic could support a date in the fifth or fourth century for the extant written form of the book, but does not demand a second-century date.&quot; He agrees with Collins that there are &quot;clear differences&quot; between Qumran Hebrew and the Hebrew of Daniel.&lt;ref&gt;E.C. Lucas, ''Daniel'' (Apollos OT Commentary; Apollos, 2002) p. 307.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Loan words===
Three Greek words used within the text have long been considered evidence for a late dating of Daniel.  All three are terms for musical instruments: ''κιθαρις'' ([[cithara]]), ''ψαλτηριον'' ([[psaltery]]) and ''συμφωνια'' ([[symphonia]]). The existence of the Greek word ''symphonia'' was cited by Rowlings as having its earliest known use in the 2nd century BC, but it has subsequently been shown that Pythagoras, born in the 6th century BC, used the term,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book
  | title = The Pythagorean Sourcebook and Library
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=EigQoSZCUAwC&amp;pg=PA334&amp;lpg=PA334&amp;dq=symphonia+GREEK+PYTHAGORAS
  | accessdate =
  | isbn = 9780933999510
  | author1 = Guthrie, Kenneth Sylvan
  | author2 = Fideler, David R
  | year = 1987 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book
  | title = The Face of Immortality: Physiognomy and Criticism
  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=dyC1LXCx73QC&amp;pg=PA30&amp;lpg=PA30&amp;dq=symphonia+GREEK+PYTHAGORAS
  | accessdate =
  | isbn = 9780791462638
  | author1 = Stimilli, Davide
  | year = 2005 }}&lt;/ref&gt;  while its adjectival use meaning &quot;in unison&quot; is found in the ''Hymni Homerica, ad Mercurium 51''; both instances date from the 6th century BC, the supposed setting of Daniel.

It is known that &quot;Greek mercenaries and slaves served in the Babylonian and Assyrian periods, some of whom were undoubtedly versed in Greek music and musical instruments.&quot; It has been speculated{{By whom|date=January 2011}} that this would explain the existence of the three Greek musical terms in Daniel's book. On the other hand, it has been claimed that the non-existence of other Greek words is a strong witness against the theory of the writing of the book in the Hellenistic period, since &quot;it is inconceivable that Greek terms for government and administration would not have been adopted into Aramaic by the second century BC&quot;&lt;ref&gt;[[Frank E. Gaebelein]], ''The Expositor's Bible Commentary'', Vol. 7, Zondervan, 1985, p. 21.&lt;/ref&gt; Even [[John Goldingay]], a proponent of the late date, admits &quot;the Greek words hardly necessitate a very late date.&quot; &lt;ref&gt;John E. Goldingay, Daniel, (Word Biblical Commentary, 30; Dallas: Word Books, 1989), p. xxv.&lt;/ref&gt;

There are also nineteen Persian loan-words in the book, most of them having to do with governmental positions. Judea was under Persian administration for two centuries until the arrival of [[Alexander the Great]] in 333 BC.

===Use of the word 'Chaldeans'===
The book of Daniel uses the term &quot;[[Chaldea]]n&quot; to refer both to an ethnic group, and to astrologers in general.  According to Montgomery and Hammer {{Citation needed|date=July 2009}} Daniel's use of the word 'Chaldean' to refer to astrologers in general is an [[anachronism]], as during the Neo-Babylonian and early Persian periods (when Daniel is said to have lived), it referred only to an ethnicity. {{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} (Compare the later [[Chaldean Oracles]]).

==Unity of Daniel==
There exists a broad consensus among scholars that the legendary stories of chapters 1-6 are almost certainly older than the visions in chapters 7-12.&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.com.au/books?id=X-XYJ0yp140C&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=The+book+of+Daniel:+composition+and+reception+John+Joseph+Collins,+Peter+W.+Flint,+Cameron+VanEpps&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=zLmCM-SJYN&amp;sig=FR1Y-2FdZVPmNRsiMqTqbYvcbLU&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=4Wm9TP3ZEcHXcb6VwMQN&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=1&amp;ved=0CBkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false Collins, John Joseph, Flint, Peter W., VanEpps, Cameron (eds)' &quot;The book of Daniel: composition and reception&quot; (Brill, 2001)] p.2&lt;/ref&gt; The wide differences between the oldest manuscripts of chapters 4-6 suggests that these chapters originally circulated separately from the rest of the book and may have been transmitted orally,&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.com.au/books?id=X-XYJ0yp140C&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=The+book+of+Daniel:+composition+and+reception+John+Joseph+Collins,+Peter+W.+Flint,+Cameron+VanEpps&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=zLmCM-SJYN&amp;sig=FR1Y-2FdZVPmNRsiMqTqbYvcbLU&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=4Wm9TP3ZEcHXcb6VwMQN&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=1&amp;ved=0CBkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false Collins, John Joseph, Flint, Peter W., VanEpps, Cameron (eds)' &quot;The book of Daniel: composition and reception&quot; (Brill, 2001)] p.3&lt;/ref&gt; and it is clear that the stories and visions that make up the book as we now have it were selected from a wider corpus of Daniel literature available to the author(s).&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.com.au/books?id=X-XYJ0yp140C&amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;dq=The+book+of+Daniel:+composition+and+reception+John+Joseph+Collins,+Peter+W.+Flint,+Cameron+VanEpps&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=zLmCM-SJYN&amp;sig=FR1Y-2FdZVPmNRsiMqTqbYvcbLU&amp;hl=en&amp;ei=4Wm9TP3ZEcHXcb6VwMQN&amp;sa=X&amp;oi=book_result&amp;ct=result&amp;resnum=1&amp;ved=0CBkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false Collins, John Joseph, Flint, Peter W., VanEpps, Cameron (eds)' &quot;The book of Daniel: composition and reception&quot; (Brill, 2001)] p.4&lt;/ref&gt;

==Christian uses of Daniel==
{{Christian Eschatology}}

The &quot;Song of the Three Holy Youths&quot; is part of the [[Matins]] service in [[Eastern Orthodoxy]], and of [[Lauds]] on Sundays and feast days in [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]].

The various episodes in the first half of the book are used by Christians as moral stories, and are often believed to foreshadow events in the [[gospel]]s.

The apocalyptic section is important to Christians for the image of the &quot;one like a [[son of Man]]&quot; (Dan. 7:13),&lt;ref&gt;[http://bible.cc/daniel/7-13.htm Parallel translations of Daniel 7:13]&lt;/ref&gt; and Jesus is presented using the same wording in the [[Book of Revelation]] in 1:13-15.&lt;ref name=Bromiley1995&gt;{{Cite book| title = International Standard Bible Encyclopedia: K-P Volume 3 of The International Standard Bible Encyclopedia| url = http://books.google.com/?id=r7QTYwYvvx0C&amp;pg=PA800| year = 1995| author = Bromiley, Geoffrey W.| publisher = Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing| page = 800 | isbn = 9780802837837| ref = harv| postscript = &lt;!--None--&gt;}}&lt;/ref&gt; The connection with Daniel's vision (as opposed to the usage in the [[Book of Ezekiel]]) is made explicit in the Gospels of [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]] and [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]] (Matt. 26:64; Mark 14:62).&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book| last1 = Collins | first1 = John Joseph | last2 = Flint | first2 = Peter W. | last3 = VanEpps | first3 = Cameron. | title = The book of Daniel : composition and receptio | year = 2001 | publisher = Brill | location = Leiden ; Boston | isbn = 978-90-04-12202-4 | page = 543  | url = http://books.google.com/?id=NuZlNCGRaPkC&amp;pg=PA543 }}&lt;/ref&gt; According to the gospels, [[Jesus]] used the title &quot;Son of Man&quot; as his preferred name for himself (Matt. 26:64; Mark 14:62). Christians sometimes see this as a claim by Jesus that he is the [[Messiah]].  According to the [[New American Bible]] and some Christian theologians, &quot;one like a son of man&quot; represents &quot;the saints of the Most High&quot; as interpreted in the vision later (Dan 7:16-18, 21-22, 25-27) and Jesus made the title &quot;Son of Man&quot; a distinguishing self reference.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.usccb.org/nab/bible/daniel/daniel7.htm#foot8 New American Bible]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.com/books?id=GP2VY68mp7AC&amp;pg=PA233 Introducing the New Testament: its literature and theology], [[Paul J. Achtemeier]], Joel B. Green, Marianne Meye Thompson&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.ca/books?id=EcsQknxV-xQC&amp;pg=PA64 An introduction to the New Testament and the origins of Christianity], Delbert Royce Burkett&lt;/ref&gt; Later Jewish interpreters interpreted this figure as the Jewish [[Messiah]]. Such interpretation appears in the [[Book of Enoch|Similitudes of Enoch]] and [[4 Ezra]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book| last1 = Reynolds | first1 = Benjamin E. | title = The apocalyptic son of man in the gospel of John | url = http://books.google.com/?id=S_lMRtGEuAsC&amp;pg=PA43 | year = 2008 | publisher = Mohr Siebeck | location = Tübingen | isbn = 978-3-16-149726-1 | page = 43 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;christian_origins_and_the_question_of_god&quot;&gt;{{Cite book| last1 = Wright | first1 = N. T. | title = Christian origins and the question of God | url = http://books.google.com/?id=PuTxOT4syCkC&amp;pg=PA316 | year = 1992 | publisher = Fortress Press | location = Minneapolis  | isbn = 978-0-8006-2681-5 | page = 316 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Traditional Christians have embraced the prophecies of the Book of Daniel, as they believe they were clearly advised by their [[Christ|Messiah]], Jesus, to be watchful for their fulfillment in the &quot;[[end times]]&quot; of this world. In the [[Olivet discourse]] ({{bibleverse||Mark|13:14|NIV}}, {{bibleverse||Matt.|24:15|NIV}}) Jesus applies Daniel's prophecy of a [[desolating sacrilege]] set up in the temple (Dan. 9:27, 11:31) to a future event—the [[siege of Jerusalem (70)|CE 70 destruction of Jerusalem]].&lt;ref&gt;[[Craig Blomberg]], Jesus and the Gospels, Apollos 1997, pp.322-326&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;christian_origins_and_the_question_of_god_a01&quot;&gt;{{Cite book| last1 = Wright | first1 = N. T. | title = Christian origins and the question of God. Volume 2, Jesus and the victory of God| url =http://books.google.com/?id=ms-xtRQoLUIC&amp;pg=PA352 | year = 1992 | publisher = Fortress Press | location = Minneapolis  | isbn = 0-8006-2682-6 | page = 352 }}&lt;/ref&gt; According to Jesus' words, this event would involve the leveling of the temple, flight from Judea, and would happen in Jesus' own generation (Mark 13: 2-4, 14, 30).  Many Christians today re-apply this prediction to a final tribulation immediately preceding [[last judgment|Judgement Day]]. Some consider the [[Prophecy of Seventy Weeks]] to be particularly compelling due to what they interpret to be prophetic accuracy.

According to some scholars, Dan. 12:2 is the earliest clear reference in the Hebrew Scriptures to the [[resurrection of the dead]],&lt;ref&gt;Hartman and Di Lella, 1990, p.&amp;nbsp;419&lt;/ref&gt; with many &quot;countrymen&quot; awakening from death, some to eternal life and some to eternal disgrace. This belief is also expressed in [[2 Maccabees]] and is linked, as in Daniel, with the idea of divine retribution.&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.ca/books?id=WtnR-6_PlJAC&amp;pg=PA1444 Encyclopedia of theology: the concise Sacramentum mundi],  Karl Rahner&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;2 Macc. 7:14 : &quot;And when he was now ready to die, he spoke thus: It is better, being put to death by men, to look for hope from God, to be raised up again by him; for, as to thee (Antiochus Epiphanes), thou shalt have no resurrection unto life&quot;.&lt;/ref&gt; The notion of [[resurrection]] was to be elaborated in the New Testament and Christian doctrine.

==Poly-traditional tomb sites of Daniel==
{{Main|Daniel's Tomb}}
There are six different locations all claimed to be the site of the tomb: [[Babylon]], [[Kirkuk]] and [[Muqdadiyah]] in [[Iraq]], [[Susa]] and [[Malamir, Iran|Malamir]] in [[Iran]], and [[Samarkand]] in [[Uzbekistan]].

