==Other notable seasons and team records==
*Pedro Martínez compiled a 1.74 ERA in a hitter's park in a big-hitting era in 2000.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/m/martipe02.shtml|title=Pedro Martinez Statistics&amp;nbsp;— Baseball-Reference.com&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*Nomar Garciaparra hit .372 in 2000, the club record for a right-handed hitter.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/g/garcino01.shtml |title=Nomar Garciaparra Statistics&amp;nbsp;— Baseball-Reference.com|author=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt;
*David Ortiz in 2005 had 47 home runs and 148 RBIs. He also had many game winning and timely hits and came in second in the MVP voting to the New York Yankees' Alex Rodriguez.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/o/ortizda01.shtml |title=David Ortiz Statistics&amp;nbsp;— Baseball-Reference.com|author=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=February 17, 2008 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt;
*David Ortiz had a franchise record-breaking 2006 season with 54 home runs in the regular season
*On April 22, 2007, Manny Ramírez, J.D. Drew, Mike Lowell, and Jason Varitek hit four consecutive home runs in the 3rd inning off 10 pitches from [[Chase Wright]] of the New York Yankees in his second Major League start and his fourth above Single-A ball. This was the fifth time in Major League history, and first time in Red Sox history this feat has occurred. Notable is that J.D. Drew had previously contributed to a four consecutive home run sequence on September 18, 2006 (coincidentally also the second batter in the sequence) while with the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]. Additionally, Red Sox manager Terry Francona's father, [[Tito Francona]], also was a part of such a four consecutive home run sequence for the [[Cleveland Indians]] in 1963.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070422&amp;content_id=1925045&amp;vkey=news_bos&amp;fext=.jsp&amp;c_id=bos|title=Sox tie mark with four straight homers &lt;nowiki&gt;|&lt;/nowiki&gt; redsox.com: News|accessdate=June 18, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*The overall regular season winning percentage since club inception in 1901 is .516, a record of 8595–8065 for games played through 9 July 2008. They started 2007 with winning percentage of 0.512 (8444–7960).&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/|title=Baseball Teams and Baseball Team Encyclopedias&amp;nbsp;— Baseball-Reference.com&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* On September 1, 2007, Clay Buchholz no-hit the [[2007 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]] in his second Major League start. He is the first Red Sox rookie and 17th Red Sox pitcher to throw a no-hitter.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://insider.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3001530&amp;name=Neyer_Rob|title=ESPN.com&amp;nbsp;— Blogs&amp;nbsp;— Rob Neyer Blog&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*On September 22, 2007, with a victory over the [[2007 Tampa Bay Devil Rays season|Tampa Bay Devil Rays]], the Red Sox clinched a spot in the postseason for the fourth time in five years, the first time in club history this has happened. Also, with this postseason berth, manager Terry Francona becomes the first manager in team history to lead the club to three playoff appearances.
*On September 8, 2008, the Red Sox set a Major League record with their 456th consecutive home-park sellout. The previous record had been held by the Cleveland Indians, who sold out 455 games between June 12, 1995 and April 2, 2001. The streak began on May 15, 2003 against the [[2003 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]]. The Red Sox are only the fourth team to sell out every home game of an entire season (the [[1996 Colorado Rockies season|1996 Colorado Rockies]] and the [[2000 San Francisco Giants season|2000 San Francisco Giants]] being the other two).&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://news.bostonherald.com/sports/baseball/red_sox/view/2008_09_04_Red_Sox_ties_sellout_streak:_Terry_Francona_a_big_fan_of_support/srvc=home&amp;position=also |title=Red Sox tie sellout streak|author=Jeff Horrigan for The Boston Herald |accessdate=September 7, 2008 |format= |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; (The team's definition of a sellout: &quot;The criteria used for a sellout at Fenway Park have been the same since the early 1990s,&quot; Kennedy said in an e-mail. &quot;Our policy is simple and straightforward, and is used by many MLB clubs &lt;nowiki&gt;[and other sports teams around the country]&lt;/nowiki&gt;. A sellout occurs when the number of tickets distributed to spectators is equal to or greater than the seating capacity at Fenway Park. &lt;nowiki&gt;[The 2008 seating capacity is 36,984 for day games and 37,400 for night games.]&lt;/nowiki&gt;&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080904&amp;content_id=3417965&amp;vkey=news_bos&amp;fext=.jsp&amp;c_id=bos&amp;partnerId=rss_bos|title=Red Sox to set MLB sellout record|accessdate=July 28, 2009|date=September 4, 2008|first=Ian|last=Browne|work=MLB.com}}&lt;/ref&gt; That is: a sellout only covers ticket sales, not spectators in physical seats.)
*As of July 18, 2010 the Red Sox reached their 600th home game sellout, second only to the Portland Trail Blazers American professional sports record of 744 between 1977 and 1995.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.nesn.com/2010/07/red-sox-sellout-streak-hits-600-games.html&lt;/ref&gt;
*On May 21, 2011, the Red Sox will be playing against the Chicago Cubs; a team the Sox last played against 93 years ago in 1918. Both teams will be wearing uniforms that match the style worn in 1918.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.boston.com/sports/baseball/redsox/extras/extra_bases/2011/05/red_sox_to_turn.html Red Sox to &quot;turn back the clock&quot; on Saturday against the Cubs]&lt;/ref&gt;

