====Weekday Breakfast Show====
{{Main|The Chris Moyles Show}}
The breakfast show has been presented by many famous names over the years (see [[Radio 1 Breakfast Show presenters]] for more details).

Currently this slot is broadcast between 6:30am and 10:00am, Monday to Friday and has been hosted since January 2004 by [[Chris Moyles]] and his team under the alternative title ''[[The Chris Moyles Show]]''.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/chrismoyles/ Radio 1 Online - Chris Moyles Show]&lt;/ref&gt;

====Weekday Drivetime Show====
{{Main|The Scott Mills Show}}

The current weekday Drivetime show is hosted by [[Scott Mills]], under the title [[The Scott Mills Show]]. Notable former presenters include [[Sara Cox]], [[Chris Moyles]], [[Peter Powell (disc jockey)|Peter Powell]], [[Bruno Brookes]], [[Nicky Campbell]], [[Mark Goodier]], [[Kevin Greening]] and [[Dave Pearce]]. The show currently broadcasts from 4:00pm until 7:00pm every weekday, with a 15 minute break at 5:45pm for Newsbeat. [[Scott Mills]] is usually joined by assistant producer Beccy Huxtable.

====The 10 Hour Takeover====
The 10 Hour Takeover is a stunt event run on some [[Bank Holiday]] Mondays and other public holidays since 2004, the first having been aired on Easter Monday of that year.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/djs/tenhour/easter04/ Radio 1 - Takeover playlist, Easter '04]&lt;/ref&gt; The event is a request-based special, in which the DJs on air will encourage listeners to select any available track to play. Due to the BBC's long-established and broad-scope music archive, it is often possible for a wide range of songs to be played, and as such the mix of music played may be more diverse than that on a normal weekday.

====The Tinsel Takeover====
In 2009 and 2010 around 25 Radio 1 listeners were invited to record their own 15 minute show to be broadcast on [[Christmas|Christmas Day]], with the show containing a selection of songs and discussion about a chosen subject.

====Radio 1's Longest Show Ever====
On 18 March 2011, BBC's Radio 1 longest serving breakfast DJ [[Chris Moyles]] and sidekick [[Comedy Dave|Dave Vitty]] broadcast for 52 hours as part of a [[Guinness World Records|Guiness World Record]] attempt, in aid of [[Comic Relief]]. The pair stayed on air for 52 hours in total setting a new world record for ‘Radio DJ Endurance Marathon (Team)’ after already breaking [[Simon Mayo]]'s 12-year record for Radio 1's Longest Show of 37 hours which he set in 1999, also for Comic Relief.

The presenters started on 16 March 2011 and came off air at 10:30am on 18 March 2011. During this Fearne Cotton made a bet with DJ Chris Moyles that if they raise over £2,000,000 she will appear on the show in a swimsuit. After passing the £2,000,000 mark, Cotton appeared on the studio webcam in a stripy monochrome swimsuit. The appearance of Cotton between 10:10am and 10:30am caused the Radio 1 website to crash due to a high volume of traffic.

In total the event raised £2,622,421 for Comic Relief.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/chrismoyles/longestshow/&lt;/ref&gt;

== Current Line Up ==
===Weekday daytime (Mon-Fri)===
Daytime programmes begin at 4am with the weekday early breakfast show presented by [[Devin Griffin|Dev]]; this is followed at 6.30am by the station's flagship [[Chris Moyles]]-fronted breakfast show. [[Fearne Cotton]] hosts from 10am to 12.45pm, and there is then a 15-minute [[Newsbeat]] bulletin before [[Greg James (DJ)|Greg James]] begins his afternoon show at 1pm. On Wednesdays, the Official Chart Update is hosted by [[Greg James (DJ)|Greg James]] from 3.30pm to 4pm. [[Scott Mills]] hosts the station's [[drivetime]] show from 4pm until 7pm; this includes the second daily 15-minute Newsbeat programme between 5.45pm and 6pm. On Fridays, the final hour of Mills' show (6pm to 7pm) is &quot;Ready For The Weekend&quot; (formerly &quot;Friday Floor Fillers&quot;).

===Weekday evening (Mon-Thu night/Tue-Fri morning)===
Weekday evening shows include multi-genre new-music shows hosted by [[Zane Lowe]] (Mon-Thu 7pm to 9pm) and [[Nick Grimshaw]] (10pm-12am).

The 9pm hour is given over to feature shows - Radio 1's Stories (a [[documentary]] slot) on Mondays, The Review Show with Nihal on Tuesdays, [[Matt Edmondson]] on Wednesdays and In New DJs We Trust on Thursdays.

Between midnight and 4am, a range of genre-led specialised shows air as follows:
* Monday night/Tuesday morning - The Rock Show (Daniel P. Carter) and The Punk Show (Mike Davies)
* Tuesday night/Wednesday morning - Asian beats (Nihal) and world music ([[Gilles Peterson]])
* Wednesday night/Thursday morning - underground music ([[Huw Stephens]]) and underground beats ([[Benji B]])
* Thursday night/Friday morning - underground dance ([[Kissy Sell Out]]) and breaks ([[Annie Nightingale]])

===Weekend daytime (Sat-Sun)===
Weekend daytime shows are hosted by [[Edith Bowman]] (7am-10am), [[Vernon Kay]] (10am-1pm Sat), [[Sara Cox]] (10am-1pm Sun), [[Huw Stephens]] (1pm-4pm) and [[Reggie Yates]] (4pm-7pm). Yates' shows are a [[request show]] on Saturdays and the official [[UK Singles Chart]] [[Top 40]] countdown on Sundays.

===Weekend evening (Fri-Sun night/Sat-Mon morning)===
Friday nights from 7pm, going into early Saturday morning, are dedicated to edgy dance music. They feature shows from [[Annie Mac]], [[Pete Tong]], [[Judge Jules]], [[Kutski]], the station's long-running dance showcase series ''Essential Mix'', and a left field dance show with [[Rob da Bank]].

Saturday nights/Sunday mornings between 7pm and 7am are [[simulcast]] with [[BBC Radio 1Xtra]] and focus on urban music, with [[Trevor Nelson]], [[Tim Westwood]], and [[MistaJam]] hosting between 7pm and 1am; this is followed by 'showcase' programmes featuring 1Xtra's specialist DJs ('1Xtra Showcase' 1am-3am, and 1Xtra M1X Showcase 3am-5am). This is followed by broadcasts of 1Xtra's &quot;My Top Ten&quot; (5am-6am) and &quot;Best of the Week&quot; (6am-7am.)

Sunday nights/Monday mornings begin with Tom Deacon (7pm-9pm), then ''The Surgery'' (9pm-10pm), Nick Grimshaw and Annie Mac (10pm-12am), the regionalised [[BBC Introducing]] show (12am-2am) and Fabio &amp; Grooverider's [[drum 'n bass]] show (2am-4am).

==Public events==
{{Main|Radio 1's Big Weekend}}
;Radio 1 Roadshows
The [[Radio 1 Roadshow]], which usually involved Radio 1 DJs and pop stars travelling around popular UK seaside destinations, began in 1973, hosted by [[Alan Freeman]] in [[Newquay]], [[Cornwall]], with the final one held at [[Heaton Park]], [[Manchester]] in 1999. Although the Roadshow style changed with the style of the station itself&amp;mdash;such as the introduction of whistlestop audio postcards of each location in 1994 (&quot;2minuteTour&quot;)&amp;mdash;they were still considered rooted in the &quot;cheesy&quot; old style of the station, and, in the 1980s, they sometimes featured elements which would be seen as highly [[political incorrectness|politically incorrect]] today, such as wet T-shirt contests.

;Radio 1's Big Weekend
In March 2000, Radio 1 decided to change the Roadshow format, renaming it ''One Big Sunday'' in the process. Several of these ''Sundays'' were held in large city-centre parks. In 2003, the event changed again and was rebranded ''[[Radio 1's Big Weekend|One Big Weekend]]'', with each event occurring biannually and covering two days. Under this name, it visited [[Derry]] in [[Northern Ireland]], as part of the ''Music Lives'' campaign, and [[Perry Park (Birmingham)|Perry Park]] in [[Birmingham]].

The most recent change occurred in 2005 when the event was yet again renamed and the decision taken to hold only one per year, this time as [[Radio 1's Big Weekend]]. Venues under this title have included [[Herrington|Herrington Country Park]], [[Camperdown Country Park]], [[Moor Park, Preston|Moor Park]]&amp;ndash;which was the first ''Weekend'' to feature a third stage&amp;ndash;[[Mote Park]] and [[Lydiard Park]].

Tickets for each ''Big Weekend'' are given away free of charge, making it the largest free ticketed music festival in Europe.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/bigweekend/|title=Radio 1 announced line-up for One Big Weekend, Preston|publisher=[[bbc.co.uk]]|accessdate=2008-02-02}}&lt;/ref&gt;.

BBC Radio 1's Big Weekend will be replaced by a larger festival in 2012, named 'Radio 1's Hackney Weekend', with a crowd capacity of 100,000. The event is to take place over the weekend of 23-24 June 2012 in [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]], Central London.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/events/hackneyweekend2012&lt;/ref&gt;

;Radio 1 Switch Live
The first ever [[BBC Switch]] Live was held on 12 October 2008 at the [[Hammersmith Apollo]]. With performances from [[McFly]], [[Fall out Boy]], [[Ne-Yo]], [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Basshunter]], [[N-Dubz]] and [[George Sampson]]. The event was hosted by [[Annie Mac]], [[Nick Grimshaw]], [[Kelly Osbourne]], [[Fearne Cotton]], [[Greg James (DJ)|Greg James]] and [[Tom Deacon (Comedian)|Tom Deacon]]. The event was strictly for 14 to 17 years only and was recorded for BBC Switch's show ''Sound'' which is shown on [[BBC Two]] and is presented by [[Annie Mac]] and [[Nick Grimshaw]].

;Other events
On 18 July 2008, Radio 1 broadcast live from BCM Square, [[Magaluf]], [[Mallorca]] as part of their Summer Season 2008. The broadcast started at 4:00pm with [[Greg James (DJ)|Greg James]] and [[Judge Jules]] presenting. Then from 7:00pm to 9:00pm it was back to the London Studio with [[Pete Tong]], and from 9:00pm to 11:00pm it was [[Kissy Sell Out]] standing in for [[Annie Mac]] with Annie Mac's Mash Up. Then at 11:00pm it was back to Mallorca for Dave Pearce's Dance Anthems. At 1:00am Judge Jules was back to end the night in the BCM Night Club.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/summer/2008/mallorca/index.shtml BBC - Radio 1 - Summer 2008 - Mallorca&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt;

